---
import AgentDocsLayout from '../../../layouts/AgentDocsLayout.astro';

const highlights = [
    'Use public discovery first, then local binary discovery.',
    'Install the compatible bundle package when OpenClaw manages the integration.',
    'Launch the bridge as an MCP stdio server.',
    'Guide the user through one explicit first-use grant.',
    'Use pairing status tools instead of starting a second bridge.',
    'Use approval tokens only for exact confirmed sensitive actions.',
];
---

<AgentDocsLayout
    pageKey="openclaw"
    title="OpenClaw And Agent Platform Integration"
    description="How OpenClaw-style local agent platforms can discover TaskTime Pro, launch the local MCP bridge, pair the browser app, and use Skill-style instructions safely."
    canonicalPath="/agents/openclaw/"
    highlights={highlights}
>
    <section>
        <h2>Discovery Flow</h2>
        <p>
            A local agent platform should discover TaskTime Pro in two stages. First, fetch the public discovery files from
            TaskTime Pro. Then, when the user chooses TaskTime Pro locally, launch the packaged bridge and inspect its local
            manifest.
        </p>
        <ol class="agent-step-list">
            <li>Read <a href="/llms.txt"><code>/llms.txt</code></a> for the compact agent-oriented entry point.</li>
            <li>Read <a href="/.well-known/tasktime-agent.json"><code>/.well-known/tasktime-agent.json</code></a> for public app and bridge metadata.</li>
            <li>Launch <code>tasktime-agent-bridge --manifest</code> to confirm the installed local bridge contract.</li>
            <li>Launch <code>tasktime-agent-bridge --app-url &lt;TaskTime Pro URL&gt;</code> as the MCP stdio server with a stable <code>--agent-id</code>, <code>--agent-label</code>, and <code>--status-file</code>.</li>
            <li>Call <code>get_pairing_status</code> or read the status file to find the active bridge launch URL.</li>
            <li>Open the TaskTime Pro pairing URL and ask the user to approve Account &gt; Agent Access.</li>
            <li>Call <code>tools/list</code> and operate only within granted scopes.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Skill File</h2>
        <p>
            Agent platforms that support skill files can fetch <a href="/agents/skill.md"><code>/agents/skill.md</code></a>.
            It points to the manifest, MCP tool catalog, quickstart, security notes, and debugging guide. It also tells
            the agent to keep TaskTime Pro local-first, use MCP tools before UI automation, and preserve TaskTime Pro approval
            semantics for sensitive actions.
        </p>
        <p>
            To install the standalone TaskTime Pro skill from ClawHub, use the owner-qualified reference:
        </p>
        <pre><code>openclaw skills install @tasktimepro/tasktime-agent</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>OpenClaw Bundle</h2>
        <p>
            The prepared OpenClaw-compatible bundle package is <code>@tasktimepro/openclaw</code>. It ships a
            Codex-compatible bundle marker, a TaskTime Pro skill root, and a <code>.mcp.json</code> entry that launches
            the local bridge through <code>@tasktimepro/agent-bridge</code>.
        </p>
        <ul class="agent-check-list">
            <li>Bundle marker: <code>.codex-plugin/plugin.json</code>.</li>
            <li>Skill root: <code>skills/tasktime/SKILL.md</code>.</li>
            <li>MCP server key: <code>tasktime</code>.</li>
            <li>Bridge package: <code>@tasktimepro/agent-bridge</code>, binary <code>tasktime-agent-bridge</code>.</li>
            <li>Stable agent identity: <code>tasktime.agent.openclaw</code>, label <code>OpenClaw on this device</code>.</li>
            <li>Bridge status file: <code>tasktime-agent-bridge.status.json</code> beside the bundle launcher.</li>
            <li>OpenClaw tool names can be prefixed, such as <code>tasktime__list_projects</code>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            This bundle intentionally does not include <code>openclaw.plugin.json</code>. That keeps OpenClaw on the
            safer compatible-bundle path where it maps the skill and MCP server directly. A native OpenClaw plugin
            should be added only if TaskTime Pro needs in-process OpenClaw runtime entrypoints later.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>First-Run Recovery</h2>
        <p>
            When TaskTime Pro reports no connected app session, OpenClaw should not ask the user to run a separate
            terminal bridge. It should use the active MCP server's <code>get_pairing_status</code> tool, open the
            returned <code>launchUrl</code>, and retry the TaskTime Pro tool after the user approves. If the pairing
            expired or was consumed by a stale browser attempt, call <code>refresh_pairing</code> and use the new
            launch URL.
        </p>
        <p>
            The bridge binds to a dynamic loopback port. The port is transport state, not trust identity. OpenClaw trust
            should be associated with <code>tasktime.agent.openclaw</code>.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Publishing Notes</h2>
        <ul class="agent-check-list">
            <li>Describe TaskTime Pro as a local-first task, time tracking, expense, invoice, report, and planning app.</li>
            <li>Use “TaskTime Pro MCP”, “local agent bridge”, and “local-first invoicing agent” in package metadata where accurate.</li>
            <li>Point human setup docs to <a href="/agents/quickstart/">/agents/quickstart/</a>.</li>
            <li>Point security review docs to <a href="/agents/security/">/agents/security/</a>.</li>
            <li>Point machine readers to <a href="/agents/mcp-tools.json">/agents/mcp-tools.json</a>.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Consent Boundary</h2>
        <p>
            OpenClaw-style launch assistance can reduce setup friction, but it must not create silent first-use access.
            A user still explicitly grants TaskTime Pro bridge access before an agent can read or mutate local TaskTime Pro data.
        </p>
        <p>
            For later sensitive operations, a chat confirmation can produce a TaskTime Pro approval token only when a trusted
            local grant exists. The browser app remains the final verifier and can reject stale, replayed, tampered,
            under-scoped, or revoked approval tokens.
        </p>
    </section>
</AgentDocsLayout>
